ocr.line: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Μὴ θελήσας
ocr.sentence: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. E. F. A. A. L. πρὸς τὴν ἀνεσιν. Id, Xen. Anab. X. 4. τῷ θεῷ προσῆνω παρὰ τὴν σκάτεραν, ὡς οὕνεκα ἐνεταύθησαν. Id. ib. ἐπιτάφια καὶ σποράματα τῆς εἰρήνης διερωτῶν τῷ θεῷ. Id. de Vect. A. III. 5. τοὺς σποράματα ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῃ ἀνεχώρησεν. Id. 6. ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῃ σποράματα ἐπὶ τῶν προσηνεγκόντων ἐπέλιπεν. id. 8. σποράματα ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῃ ἐπὶ τῶν προσηνεγκόντων ἐπέλιπεν. id. 10.

Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. ocr.region: the fiery man. Essay on L. §9. P. 12, 2. If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endared.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a commenut on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ pyasus) ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in geneial. ἀέξει] Not "exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

groundtruth.region: the fiery man.’ Essay on L. § 9. p. 12, 2. If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *κατ’ ἀνδρὸς αἴθονος. These words are added as a comment on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ μέγας μῦθος] ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, ὦ μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in general. ἀέξει] Not ‘exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

Tecmessa said she wished to see him, and that the gods had made her suffer sufficiently in her heart to the loss of her father; and that she had the same sentiments as her brother, and wished him to return. He said that he had come for the sake of the god, but that he could not return without the assistance of Tecmessa, and he asked her if she would accompany him. “Soon,” she replied, “shall the day come when I shall have no wish to accompany you, for I am the daughter of the king, and the king will be my husband. Therefore, if you return to your country in safety, you must make use of another woman.” She spoke thus that she might deceive and disappoint him. So the king came down to the shore, and when he arrived at the place of the banquet, which was near to his camp, he took the woman with him, and went to the king’s camp, which was not far distant. And as he went along he found many dead bodies of the mercenaries and of the Macedonians, for there were many corpses lying about the place, some in the camp and some outside it; for the enemy had been overpowered by sleep, and were lying in a deep and profound slumber. Tecmessa said she wished to see him, and that the gods had made her suffer sufficiently in her heart to the loss of her father; and that she had the same sentiments as her brother, and wished him to return. He said that he had come for the sake of the god, but that he could not return without the assistance of Tecmessa, and he asked her if she would accompany him. “Soon,” she replied, “shall the day come when I shall have no wish to accompany you, for I am the daughter of the king, and the king will be my husband. Therefore, if you return to your country in safety, you must make use of another woman.” She spoke thus that she might deceive and disappoint him. So the king came down to the shore, and when he arrived at the place of the banquet, which was near to his camp, he took the woman with him, and went to the king’s camp, which was not far distant. And as he went along he found many dead bodies of the mercenaries and of the Macedonians, for there were many corpses lying about the place, some in the camp and some outside it; for the enemy had been overpowered by sleep, and were lying in a deep and profound slumber. ocr.region: 488. εἴπερ Trivòs] The hypothetical clause εἴπερ τις is attracted, as a sort of pronoun, into the construction of the clause on which it depends. See E. on L. § 35. p. 60, and cp. vio1. So in O. C. 734. σθένουσαν .. εἴ τιν’ Ἑλλάδος. For σθένοντος ἐν πλούτῳ, cp. Pind. Isthm. 3. 2, σθένει πλούτου; Eur. El. 939. 489. που] ‘Isuppose.’ 490. μάλιστα] ‘Above all. The power of Ajax is more manifest to Tecmessa than that of the gods them- selves, and she has learnt to adopt some- thing of his bold way of speaking about them. Cp. infr. 950-3. A single figure is now seen approaching from the opposite direction to that in which Ajax went forth. The man proves to be Teucer’s forerunner. ñ The effect of the following scene is twofold. ocr.region: κἀπ’ dpol: for this modest καί, cp. Ph. 192 εἴπερ κἀγώ τι φρονῶ, and n. on Ant. 719. Repar should naturally go with κἀπ’ ἐμοί, though βλέπειν ἐπί τινι seems to occur nowhere else, and ἐπιβλέπειν τινί only in Lucian Astr. 20 καὶ σφίσι γνομένοισι τῷ μὲν ἡ Ἀφροδίτη τῷ δὲ ὁ Ζεὺς... ἐπέβλεψαν (‘loocked with favour’). The alternative is to take ἐπ’ uol as= ‘in my case,’ and βλέψας as epexegetic ; but this is certainly harsh. 846 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν kA6pa, and ib. 1295.—mpdyn, deeds: cp. 21. Pe ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 247, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. The other plays in which Sophocles has used the eccyclema are the Antigone (1294, where see n.), and the Electra (1464 f., n.). Ajax, sitting among his victims, and meditating his own destruction, was the subject of a famous picture by Timomachus of Byzantium. Philostratus ( Vit. prediction.region: βλάπτων. αὕτη δὲ ἐπ’ αὐτῷ τὴν εὐνοίαν ἀπολαύσατο περὶ τὸ κατὰ τὴν συναίσυναν καὶ βαρβαρὴν ἀνήρα τῷ θεῷ καὶ στρατηγίᾳ τῷ πόλεμος, καὶ τὸν θεὸν ἔνοχα καὶ τὴν ἐπιθήκην ἐπέπεσε καὶ πρὸς οἶμα τῶν ἐπικενδύμων ἤθελεν κραταστῆσαι τὴν πόλιν. The description is a curious compound of Greek and oriental taste, and in no way agrees with the picture which is said to have been discovered at Rome in 1863, though the two may possibly represent separate pictures by the same artist. As the word ‘eccycletas’ occurs here (and at vv. 360 ff., and 380) for the first time in the trilogy, it is not easy to determine whether the device for this production was really a stage of the kind described above, or merely the ordinary Greek scene. There is a good chance, however, that it was the latter. The description of the 2nd scene (249) is a complete mis- interpretation of the original, the only point which it represents being the actual position of the κύκλος (see n. on 229) round Ajax, which, in the first play, as in the subsequent dramas, is always made part of the ordinary scenic background (see 229 and n.; cp. 670, where it is not on the stage). For a good account of the eccyclema, see C. Müller, 4. 169 ff.; cf. n. on 229 and 284 f.—The scene is still in the court of Agamemnon’s house, and is now brought on by Ajax himself, who comes in, as the text, noting the fact, implies, from his own house. He is followed by Teucer, who also comes out from the house, and goes up to Ajax, and the two stand together in front of the palace, facing the spectators. Teucer has been with Ajax, not in

The description is a curious compound of Greek and oriental taste, and in no way agrees with the picture which is said to have been discovered at Rome in 1863, though the two may possibly represent separate pictures by the same artist. As the word ‘eccycletas’ occurs here (and at vv. 360 ff., and 380) for the first time in the trilogy, it is not easy to determine whether the device for this production was really a stage of the kind described above, or merely the ordinary Greek scene. There is a good chance, however, that it was the latter. The description of the 2nd scene (249) is a complete mis- interpretation of the original, the only point which it represents being the actual position of the κύκλος (see n. on 229) round Ajax, which, in the first play, as in the subsequent dramas, is always made part of the ordinary scenic background (see 229 and n.; cp. 670, where it is not on the stage). For a good account of the eccyclema, see C. Müller, 4. 169 ff.; cf. n. on 229 and 284 f.—The scene is still in the court of Agamemnon’s house, and is now brought on by Ajax himself, who comes in, as the text, noting the fact, implies, from his own house. The alternative is to take ἐπ’ uol as= ‘in my case,’ and βλέψας as epexegetic ; but this is certainly harsh. 846 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν kA6pa, and ib. 1295.—mpdyn, deeds: cp. 21. Pe ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 247, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. The other plays in which Sophocles has used the eccyclema are the Antigone (1294, where see n.), and the Electra (1464 f., n.). prediction.region: βλάπτων. αὕτη δὲ ἐπ’ αὐτῷ τὴν εὐνοίαν ἀπολαύσατο περὶ τὸ κατὰ τὴν συναίσυναν καὶ βαρβαρὴν ἀνήρα τῷ θεῷ καὶ στρατηγίᾳ τῷ πόλεμος, καὶ τὸν θεὸν ἔνοχα καὶ τὴν ἐπιθήκην ἐπέπεσε καὶ πρὸς οἶμα τῶν ἐπικενδύμων ἤθελεν κραταστῆσαι τὴν πόλιν. The description is a curious compound of Greek and oriental taste, and in no way agrees with the picture which is said to have been discovered at Rome in 1863, though the two may possibly represent separate pictures by the same artist. As the word ‘eccycletas’ occurs here (and at vv. 360 ff., and 380) for the first time in the trilogy, it is not easy to determine whether the device for this production was really a stage of the kind described above, or merely the ordinary Greek scene. There is a good chance, however, that it was the latter. The description of the 2nd scene (249) is a complete mis- interpretation of the original, the only point which it represents being the actual position of the κύκλος (see n. on 229) round Ajax, which, in the first play, as in the subsequent dramas, is always made part of the ordinary scenic background (see 229 and n.; cp. 670, where it is not on the stage). For a good account of the eccyclema, see C. Müller, 4. 169 ff.; cf. n. on 229 and 284 f.—The scene is still in the court of Agamemnon’s house, and is now brought on by Ajax himself, who comes in, as the text, noting the fact, implies, from his own house. He is followed by Teucer, who also comes out from the house, and goes up to Ajax, and the two stand together in front of the palace, facing the spectators. Teucer has been with Ajax, not in

ocr.sentence: 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere.
ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

[178] The word ὕλη is used by Aristotle, Rhet. iv. 1. 11, 85, of the material objects by which men are influenced in their reasoning (as in the phrase πρὸς ἀρχαίους ἡμῶν ὕλης); and in the Rhet. i. 2, 18, of the passions, the objects of which are desirable or undesirable things. Plato also uses ὕλη in the same way as Aristotle (e.g. Soph. Rep. 220, E. 196, Protag. 321, 338, and others). The word φύσις on the other hand (of which φύσεις is the plural), denotes an essence. The passage under discussion (480) seems to mean that the soul is the form or essence which is common to all the physical objects, or which is contained in them; but the word ὕλη does not seem to be the most appropriate for this purpose.

ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

A. 748: δι’ ἀετός κακοῦ γέγοναν ὅπως δύνατοι δ’ ἀτοπώθεσθαι: “they were brought to ruin by the unkindness of the eagle.” For the words ἀετὸς and κακός, cp. Ael. 15. 31: τῶν ἀετῶν κακῶν. 667 n. 4: ‘of a man, to his own advantage, and to the disadvantage of another.’ The phrase κατὰ κρίσιν is found elsewhere: see the notes on 720 and 910. 681 νήπιον in the singular, not in the plural: see 707 f1. 687 cp. 650 n. 1: cp. Theogn. 1464. 688 f1. Sr. It would be more usual to say ἀνακαλύφας; cp. 660, 672. 694 f1.

prediction.region: enitive with a pronom. which denotes the person to whom he is addressed; not simply with a pronoun: cp. 662. 649 n3: ‘as is the common expression of men (not the common expression of men’s’). The word is inappropriate to the context, and has been omitted.—eipaxv, “to bring to mind, to recapitulate:” in Ph. 452, 491. 672 rv. 8, and Ph. 540.—pav: ἐξηκέσατο is the pass. of ἐξέχεσθαι, a verb found in Homer: Iliad 11. 258, 267, 274. 4. 258, 271; Od. 2. 192; Od. 5. 244; Od. 6. 204; Od. 23. 535, 544.—Sr.: the word is in the dative, the construction is that of a sentence beginning with a dat. with the article: cp. 665 n3, 668.—cqv, κακῶς, ‘ill’: see the note on 653 n. 2. A. 748: δι’ ἀετός κακοῦ γέγοναν ὅπως δύνατοι δ’ ἀτοπώθεσθαι: “they were brought to ruin by the unkindness of the eagle.” For the words ἀετὸς and κακός, cp. Ael. 15. 31: τῶν ἀετῶν κακῶν. 667 n. 4: ‘of a man, to his own advantage, and to the disadvantage of another.’ The phrase κατὰ κρίσιν is found elsewhere: see the notes on 720 and 910. 681 νήπιον in the singular, not in the plural: see 707 f1. 687 cp. 650 n. 1: cp. Theogn. 1464. 688 f1. Sr. It would be more usual to say ἀνακαλύφας; cp. 660, 672. 694 f1.

Aias will gern Tekmessa loben —, nicht aber, wie der Chor räth, ihre Worte, d. h. ihr versprechen, leben zu wollen, son- dern, wie er neoa noosdoxier hinzufügt, wenn sie ihm in allen Stücken folgsam sei. prediction.region: t), was sonst furcht- er- und widerwärtiger denn der Winter? 670 ff. Die Nothwendigkeit wird noch durch die Ueberlegen- machung des Heraklides von Knidos bestärkt, der aus der Beschreibung der Atriden beiderseits der Athenergrenze und den Ber- er- anzügen und Schätzen Menelaos’ und seiner Brüder eine Anzahl von Wundern auf der Argolidenschnur nachweisen kann. — 672. Ihr erzählt, wie ihr ein Geschenk der Atriden gesandt worden sei; 674. Sie gestehen, sie hätten von den Atriden, und, wenn auch nicht die ganze, doch einen Teil ihres Schmuckes, ihrer Gewänder und Füße- werks erobert. 673 f. Menelaos bestätigt Aia- s’ Nachstellung und berichtet, die Atriden hätten in Menelaos’ Hafensitz einen Anspruch auf Schiffbrüchige geltend gemacht. 675 ff. Aias be- staetigt, er habe keinerlei Verlangen gehabt, der Bruder wieder einzufallen; Menelaos erzählt, er habe die Atriden, als er sie aufsitzen sähe, ge- herdete, sich aber von ihnen entfernen müssen. 682. Aias beteuert, nur so und so oft, und nicht oft, und nur so- wol lange gehandelt zu haben; 683. Menelaos bestätigt, daß er und nicht Aias die Atriden mit einem Geschenke überhäuft habe. 684 ff. Aias beraumt eine Ver- fügung des Geschenks, worauf die Atriden ihm das Schmeicheln mit den Verwandten und den Freunden, die Aussicht auf eine Erlaubniss mit seinem Schützling anbieten; 685 f. Menelaos erzählt, die Atriden seien von den Gefangenen befreit worden, und ihr Geschenk an Aias habe sie nicht wieder zurückerstattet. 686 ff. Aias verspricht dem Atriden, das Schmeicheln

Ihr erzählt, wie ihr ein Geschenk der Atriden gesandt worden sei; 674. Sie gestehen, sie hätten von den Atriden, und, wenn auch nicht die ganze, doch einen Teil ihres Schmuckes, ihrer Gewänder und Füße- werks erobert. 673 f. Menelaos bestätigt Aia- s’ Nachstellung und berichtet, die Atriden hätten in Menelaos’ Hafensitz einen Anspruch auf Schiffbrüchige geltend gemacht. 675 ff. Aias be- staetigt, er habe keinerlei Verlangen gehabt, der Bruder wieder einzufallen; Menelaos erzählt, er habe die Atriden, als er sie aufsitzen sähe, ge- herdete, sich aber von ihnen entfernen müssen. 682. Aias beteuert, nur so und so oft, und nicht oft, und nur so- wol lange gehandelt zu haben; 683. Menelaos bestätigt, daß er und nicht Aias die Atriden mit einem Geschenke überhäuft habe. 684 ff. Aias beraumt eine Ver- fügung des Geschenks, worauf die Atriden ihm das Schmeicheln mit den Verwandten und den Freunden, die Aussicht auf eine Erlaubniss mit seinem Schützling anbieten; 685 f. Menelaos erzählt, die Atriden seien von den Gefangenen befreit worden, und ihr Geschenk an Aias habe sie nicht wieder zurückerstattet. 686 ff. Aias verspricht dem Atriden, das Schmeicheln

Pers. 378) ἡμέρα. Vgl. El. 19. 674 f. Das Wehen heftiger Stürme beruhigt auch wie- der das seufzende Meer, indem es sanfteren Lüften (vergl Odyss. 5, 383. Virg. Aen. 5, 763.) oder der Windstille Platz macht. Gottheiten und göttlich gedachte Kräfte schalten unumschränkt auf deu Felde ihrer Thätigkeit, wie Apollon und Artemis z. B. nicht bloss schützen, sondern auch stra- fen, Hypnos 675 packt und los- lässt, zu O. C. 868. So hat Aeo- los Odyss. 10, 21 als ταμίης ἀνέ- μων die Macht, ἠμὲν παυσέμεναι ἠδʼ ὀρνύμεν ὅν κʼ ἐθέλῃσιν, wie jeder besondere Wind in seiner Sphäre, z. B. Hor. 1, 3, 15 Nolo non arbiter Hadriae maior, tol- lere seu ponere volt freta. So-
